John Edward: Language skills that are essential for global citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a track record of academic excellence, and this continued in 2018 with the help of another body of excellent exam results, further bolstered by individual and collective success in sports, arts, music and other community projects.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to deliver the best level of service to its students and their parents.
The aim of independent schools is to prepare their students for further and higher education, in their chosen career and place as global citizens.
As an educational sector that designs and implements a school curriculum, we see modern languages continue to be a popular and preferred topic of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, "If you talk to someone in a language he understands, it will go into his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it will enter his heart."
It's a strong reminder that we shouldn't just rely on the English language when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From the results of this year's exam, we can see that language is at the top of the league tables with the highest passing rates in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages earned a Higher A grade.
The data, collected from 74 SCIS member schools, showed that 72 percent of students scored Higher A in Mandarin, while 72 percent of German learners, 69 percent of French learners and 63 percent of Spanish learners also scored A.
It shows that independent schools in Scotland sport foreign languages as essential skills that young people will no doubt need in the future.
Today's languages, as the subject of choice, are considered equivalent to STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent school curricula elsewhere.
In a 2014 survey conducted by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills, it was found that among the reasons employers provided for the difficulty of filling vacant positions, 17 percent were due to a lack of language ability.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly necessary for young people to prepare for their future careers.
Along with the increase in potential job opportunities that require language knowledge, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Whatever a person's chosen career, if he learns a second language, he will have an advantage in the future due to having a lifelong ability like this.
People who speak multiple languages will automatically have the advantage because of its ability to communicate directly with people from other countries.
In 2013, according to a YouGov poll of more than 4,000 adults in the UK, 75 percent were not able to communicate in a foreign language and only French was spoken in a double-digit percentage, which was 15 percent.
This is why it is important for today's youth to invest in language teaching.
Developing multilingual skills, particularly in developing economies, will give young people a better chance of finding meaningful jobs.
In Scotland, schools are different when it comes to the languages they teach.
Many schools will focus on more classic modern languages, while others will teach languages considered most important for the UK by the year 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of your child's interests, there is always a choice of language in independent schools, with specialist teachers in this field.
Independent schools in Scotland are committed to providing a teaching environment that will prepare young people and provide them with the skills needed to be successful, regardless of their future.
It is undeniable at this time, in the area of global business, that language knowledge remains essential for the future of the country, so it must be reflected in education.
Without a doubt, modern languages should be regarded as "the power of global interaction."
Independent schools will continue to offer this option, diversity and excellence for the youth of Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
