North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that their suspicions of the United States are deepening because of continued sanctions and that the country will never unilaterally surrender its nuclear weapons under the circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly of representatives around the world that North Korea has taken "significant steps with good intentions" over the past year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, destroying nuclear test sites, and vowing not to produce nuclear weapons and technology.
"However, we have not seen an equivalent response from the United States," he said.
"While there is no confidence in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security and under such circumstances we will not really unilaterally disarm," he said.
While Ri reiterated North Korea's familiar complaints about Washington's rejection of a "stage-long" denuclearization strategy in which North Korea will be honored as it takes small steps, his statement appeared to be important because it did not immediately reject unilateral denuclearization as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement made by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between the current President of the United States and the head of North Korea in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work towards "denuclearization of the Korean peninsula" while Trump pledged to guarantee North Korea's safety.
North Korea has long sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korea War, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first give up their nuclear weapons.
Washington has also rejected requests to cut tough international sanctions on North Korea.
"The United States is pressing for denuclearization" and is raising the weight of sanctions to achieve their goals in a violent manner, and they are also protesting "declaring the end of the war," Ri said.
"The view that sanctions will bring us down is a strong dream of people who don't know about us.
But the problem is that the continued disengagement deepens our suspicions."
Ri made no mention of plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the United States head of state announced earlier in the week.
Instead, the minister announced three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months and added: "If South Korea and the United States are not the party on this issue of nuclear disarmament, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula will not lead to a deadlock."
However, the tone of Ri's speech differed greatly from last year, when he told the U.N. General Assembly that it was inevitable to target the territory of the United States of North Korea's rockets after "Mr. Evil President" Trump called Kim a "rocket man" on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who threatened last year that he would "really crush" North Korea, showered Kim with praise for his courage in taking steps to disarmament, but said there is still much work to be done and sanctions should remain until North Korea denuclearizes.
