Harvard students, take a course on getting enough rest
This year, a new course at Harvard University is helping its undergraduates get a good night's sleep in an attempt to combat the study's macho culture all night long while being powered by caffeine.
One academic found that students at the world's number one university often know nothing about the most basic ways to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, teacher of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believed was the earliest of its kind in the United States.
She was inspired to start the course after giving a question about the impact of sleep loss on learning.
‘After that, a woman came up to me and said: ‘Why didn’t you just say this to me, in my senior year?’
"She said no one told her about the value of sleep - which surprised me," she told The Telegraph.
