Paul Barreira, teacher of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health service, said the university decided to enter the course after learning that students were completely deprived of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive activities.
In one section there is a photo of the dorm room, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, shoes and books to tell about the effects of caffeine and light, and how sleep deprivation affects athleticism, and the importance of a routine for sleep.
In another section, participants were told how sleep deprivation increased the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
There is a map of the campus, with interactive icons, that encourage participants to think about their daily activities.
