National Trust detects the secret life of bats
New research conducted outside an estate in the Scottish Highlands aims to reveal how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
This is expected to shed light on the behavior of exotic flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
The study by scientists at the National Trust for Scotland will follow common and soprano pipistrelles as well as brown-eared bats and Daubenton bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations around the property to monitor the activities of the bats throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using hand-held detectors.
Expert sound analysis on all recordings will confirm the frequency of bat calls and which species make which sounds.
Next, a habitat map will be created to have a more detailed landscape-scale description of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation adviser for the NTS, hopes to reveal the results of which habitat areas are the most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to learn about the benefits of habitat management work such as the creation of fields and what is the best way to conserve woodlands for bats and other related species.
The bat population in Scotland and throughout the UK has decreased significantly over the past century.
They are threatened from construction and development work that affects nesting and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lightning can also pose a risk, as well as flypapers and some chemicals treated by building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
Bats are not really blind.
However, due to their nightly hunting, their ears are more helpful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echo-location technique to identify insects and obstacles in the path they are crossing.
Bats are important to the NTS, which is responsible for the conservation of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 acres of land nationwide.
It has trained experts, regularly conducting surveys, inspecting nests and sometimes rescues.
The organisation even established the first and only dedicated land reserve for bats in Scotland on the Threave estate at Dumfries and Galloway, which was home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
Estate manager David Thompson says the estate is the best territory for them.
"We have a good spot for the bats," he said.
"We have old buildings, many veteran trees and all the beautiful residences.
But there's still a lot we don't know about bats, so what we're doing here and in other properties can help us understand more about what they need to survive."
He emphasizes the importance of inspecting bats before carrying out maintenance within the property because it is possible that accidental destruction of at least one mother's nest could kill 400 women and young bats, potentially wiping out the entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass or disturb them or destroy their nests.
Scotland-based Bat Conservation Trust official Elisabeth Ferrell is encouraging the public to help.
He said: "We can learn more about our bats and we don't know the population of many of our species."
